%%%
Joint-bodied composite kernel — multi-output regression.

Each group g has parameters (mu_g, sigma_g). Within a group we
observe a pair (y1, y2) where y1 ~ Normal(mu_g, sigma_g) and
y2 ~ Normal(mu_g, 2*sigma_g) are conditionally independent given
the group params. The pair structure is a (keyword) `joint(...)` —
each cell of the surrounding `broadcast(...)` produces ONE joint
draw, and each draw factors as independent component samples per
spec §06.

Phase 4.2 lands the joint composite-body recogniser
(`composite-body-recognizers.ts`) and the corresponding
`_executeJointComposite` execution path in `mat-broadcast.ts`. The
classifier (`derivations.classifyKernelBroadcast`) accepts joint-
bodied user kernels alongside iid-bodied ones.

Result shape per atom: [G, C] where C = 2 components. Atom-major.

MvNormal vector-valued components defer to Phase 5.1 — MvNormal
joins the sampler REGISTRY there, after which the joint executor
handles vector components through the same kwarg-driven sampleN
dispatch without further changes.
%%%
flatppl_compat = "0.1"

G = 3  % number of groups

% Hierarchical group-level parameters.
mu_pop ~ Normal(0, 5)
tau ~ truncate(Normal(0, 2), interval(0, inf))
mus_per_group ~ iid(Normal(mu_pop, tau), G)

% Per-group noise scales (fixed-phase array — atom-indep).
sigmas_per_group = [1.0, 0.5, 0.8]

% Per-group joint observation kernel — kwarg-form, two scalar Normal
% components. Body uses placeholder names `mu`, `sigma` which the
% kernel-broadcast args (`mu = mus_per_group`, `sigma = sigmas_per_group`)
% substitute per cell.
group_kernel = kernelof(
  joint(y1 = Normal(mu = mu, sigma = sigma),
        y2 = Normal(mu = mu, sigma = mul(2.0, sigma))),
  mu = mu, sigma = sigma)

% Kernel-broadcast: per group g, draw a (y1, y2) pair with
% mu = mus_per_group[g] and sigma = sigmas_per_group[g].
y_obs = broadcast(group_kernel,
                  mu = mus_per_group,
                  sigma = sigmas_per_group)
